editorialNotes.standard: R&B/soul legend Ray Charles devoted himself to music for over six decades, scoring numerous pop, jazz, country, gospel, R&B, and soul hits — a list which includes legendary tunes like "Hallelujah I Love Her So," "A Bit of Soul," and "What'd I Say." The Genius' uniquely emotive vocals and vibrant live performances — along with his talents as an arranger, composer, and pianist — earned the Georgia native a slew of number one hits, twelve Grammys, and a dedicated fan base worldwide. With his passing in June of 2004, Ray Charles left an indelible mark on the face of pop, R&B, and soul music.

I Wanna Dance With Somebody (The Movie: Whitney New, Classic and Reimagined)

editorialNotes.standard: With her crystalline mezzo-soprano and powerful gospel range, Whitney Houston dominated the '80s pop charts and was one of the best-selling artists of all time. The daughter of Cissy Houston, cousin of Dionne Warwick, and goddaughter of Aretha Franklin, Houston was responsible for some of the best in pop and R&B—“How Will I Know,” “Saving All My Love for You,” “Greatest Love of All,” “You Give Good Love,” “I Wanna Dance With Somebody (Who Loves Me),” “Exhale (Shoop Shoop),” and “My Love Is Your Love.” Her performance of “The Star-Spangled Banner” at the 1991 Super Bowl remains the anthem’s high-water mark, and her ballistic cover of Dolly Parton’s “I Will Always Love You” threatened to upset the earth’s axis. It's these moments of musical grace which show why we will always love Whitney.
